  "biography_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\">Nicaenetus of Samos was a Hellenistic poet of the 3rd century BCE. Identified as a native of Samos, he is also at times associated with Abdera in Thrace. He was a contemporary of Aratus of Soli and, according to the Suda, a student of the poet Philicus of Corcyra, connecting him to Alexandrian literary circles.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">His work survives only in fragments. The Suda credits him with an epic poem titled Lyrkos and a collection of Epigrams. Several of these epigrams were included in Meleager&#x27;s Garland, and a few fragments are preserved in the Greek Anthology and the works of Athenaeus.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">Nicaenetus represents the lesser-known epic poets of the Hellenistic era. His inclusion in the Garland indicates his epigrams were respected, and his connection to Philicus places him within the period&#x27;s scholarly poetic tradition. His fragments provide valuable evidence for the range of themes and styles in early Hellenistic poetry beyond its most canonical figures.</p>\n</div>",
